"{\n  \"type\": \"theorem\",\n  \"name\": \"Saddle Point of a Linear System\",\n  \"hypothesis\": [\n    {\n      \"type\": \"let\",\n      \"variable\": \"<anonymous>\",\n      \"kind\": \"System of linear differential equations\",\n      \"property\": \"$\\dot{x} = y$ and $\\dot{y} = x$\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"conclusion\": \"The origin is a saddle point of the given system.\",\n  \"status\": \"incomplete proof\",\n  \"missing\": [\n    {\n      \"type\": \"problem\",\n      \"statement\": \"Show that the solution for arbitrary initial conditions except those on the eigenvector $v_2$ approaches infinity as $t \\\\rightarrow \\\\infty$.\",\n      \"solved\": false\n    }\n  ],\n  \"proof\": {\n    \"type\": \"proof\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"statement\": \"We begin by finding the general solution of the system.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"The system can be written in matrix form as $x' = \\\\begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\\\end{bmatrix} x$.\",\n        \"proof-method\": \"Rewriting the given system in matrix form.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"The characteristic equation of the matrix is $\\\\lambda^2 - 1 = 0$.\",\n        \"proof-method\": \"Using the formula for the characteristic equation of a 2x2 matrix.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"The eigenvalues are $\\\\lambda = 1$ and $\\\\lambda = -1$.\",\n        \"deduced_from\": [\n          \"The characteristic equation of the matrix is $\\\\lambda^2 - 1 = 0$.\"\n        ],\n        \"proof-method\": \"Solving the characteristic equation.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"statement\": \"Now we will find the eigenvectors corresponding to each eigenvalue.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"let\",\n        \"variable\": \"$\\\\lambda$\",\n        \"value\": \"1\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"The eigenvector corresponding to $\\\\lambda = 1$ is $v_1 = \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ 1 \\\\end{bmatrix}$.\",\n        \"calculation\": [\n          {\n            \"step\": \"$(A - \\\\lambda I) \\\\begin{bmatrix} x \\\\ y \\\\end{bmatrix} = 0$\",\n            \"justification\": \"Equation to find the eigenvector\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"step\": \"\\\\begin{bmatrix} -1 & 1 \\\\ 1 & -1 \\\\end{bmatrix} \\\\begin{bmatrix} x \\\\ y \\\\end{bmatrix} = 0\",\n            \"justification\": \"Substituting the value of $\\\\lambda$\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"step\": \"-x + y = 0\",\n            \"justification\": \"Simplifying the matrix equation\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"step\": \"x = y\",\n            \"justification\": \"Solving for x\"\n          }\n\n        ]\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"let\",\n        \"variable\": \"$\\\\lambda$\",\n        \"value\": \"-1\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"The eigenvector corresponding to $\\\\lambda = -1$ is $v_2 = \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ -1 \\\\end{bmatrix}$.\",\n        \"calculation\": [\n          {\n            \"step\": \"$(A - \\\\lambda I) \\\\begin{bmatrix} x \\\\ y \\\\end{bmatrix} = 0$\",\n            \"justification\": \"Equation to find the eigenvector\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"step\": \"\\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 \\\\end{bmatrix} \\\\begin{bmatrix} x \\\\ y \\\\end{bmatrix} = 0\",\n            \"justification\": \"Substituting the value of $\\\\lambda$\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"step\": \"x + y = 0\",\n            \"justification\": \"Simplifying the matrix equation\"\n          },\n          {\n            \"step\": \"x = -y\",\n            \"justification\": \"Solving for x\"\n          }\n        ]\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"The general solution of the system is $x(t) = c_1 e^t \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ 1 \\\\end{bmatrix} + c_2 e^{-t} \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ -1 \\\\end{bmatrix}$.\",\n        \"proof-method\": \"Using the eigenvalues and eigenvectors to construct the general solution.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"statement\": \"Now we will analyze the behavior of the solution as $t$ approaches infinity.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"Along the eigenvector $v_1 = \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ 1 \\\\end{bmatrix}$, the solution approaches infinity as $t$ approaches infinity.\",\n        \"proof-method\": \"The term $c_1 e^t \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ 1 \\\\end{bmatrix}$ dominates the solution as $t \\\\rightarrow \\\\infty$.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"Along the eigenvector $v_2 = \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ -1 \\\\end{bmatrix}$, the solution approaches 0 as $t$ approaches infinity.\",\n        \"proof-method\": \"The term $c_2 e^{-t} \\\\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\\\ -1 \\\\end{bmatrix}$ approaches 0 as $t \\\\rightarrow \\\\infty$.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"conclude\",\n        \"statement\": \"Since the solution approaches infinity along one eigenvector and 0 along the other, the origin is a saddle point.\",\n        \"error\": \"The conclusion is based on the behavior along the eigenvectors only. To prove it is a saddle point, it is necessary to show that the solution for arbitrary initial conditions (except those on the stable eigenvector) approaches infinity as  $t \\\\rightarrow \\\\infty$.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}"